equation_narrative.headline: Polar turn context drives threonine selection over hydrophobic early signal
equation_narrative.story: Position 14 in ubiquitin's beta-turn assembles a polar-favoring context through structural contacts with the adjacent turn residues. Early layers (L1-17) show a volatile logit lens reflecting mixed hydrophobic and polar signals as the model reads local sequence and four structural contacts. The representation stabilizes toward polar character by L23 (27.5% T), then decision channels activate strongly in L26-32. MLP neurons in L29-32 cast decisive votes for threonine, with T-specific features reaching 48% by L33, narrowly defeating proline (24%).

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-17 show highly volatile logit-lens trajectories with 10 lead changes as the model integrates local sequence context and four structural contacts. Early attention (L8-10) reads nearby positions without clear structural focus, producing mixed signals. The representation character shifts from serine-like (22.6% at L0) through hydrophobic phases (A peaks at 20% L12, L at 18% L10) to charged (K at 21% L8, R at 16% L15-17). By L17-23, the representation stabilizes toward polar character as turn-context features emerge, with T rising from 10% to 27% and V briefly leading at 41% L26 before the decision phase begins.
perception_phase.context_character: Beta-turn position with four structural contacts in a polar local environment (flanked by K13, I15, L8). The representation by L23 reflects polar turn character with moderate hydrophobic compatibility, consistent with the TI motif in ubiquitin's structured core.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 4 residues within contact distance, read primarily through L31-32 attention heads
Local sequence: Strong attention to adjacent positions K13 and I15 throughout perception phase
Turn context features: L18 features (F18:7475, F18:908) encode secondary structure preferences with moderate projections (6.2-6.8)
No co-evolutionary signal: 0 co-evolving positions detected, indicating local structural determination

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes in L26-32 as T-specific MLP neurons activate strongly. L26 shows the first clear T commitment (+6.7 logit velocity, MLP-driven), with N26:2159 projecting 0.73 toward T. L29-31 deliver the decisive push: N29:4973 (0.85 proj), N30:1323 (0.69 proj), and N31:3485 (0.95 proj) all vote strongly for T. Proline surges late (L32-33) via MLP channels, reaching 24% but insufficient to overtake T's 48%.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from context assembly to prediction. L23 shows mixed representation (T 27%, V rising) with general polar features. L24-25 activate the first AA-specific prediction channels: L25 MLP neurons contribute +4.7 net projection toward T, with N25:816 (0.68 proj) and N25:2435 (0.51 proj) casting explicit T votes. The representation transitions from 'polar turn position' to 'specifically threonine.'

candidates.narrative: Threonine emerges as the clear winner through sustained MLP support in L26-32. After stabilizing at 27% in L23, T rises steadily through decision layers: 30% at L26, 38% at L29, finally reaching 48% at L33. The decisive evidence comes from highly specific MLP neurons: N29:4973 (0.85 proj), N30:1323 (0.69 proj), and N31:3485 (0.95 proj) all cast strong T votes. Late-layer SAE features (F30:9045 with 57.6 proj, F33:9048 with 82.9 proj) encode T-specific prediction channels that dominate the final output.
candidates.key_layers: Commits at L26, strengthens through L29-31, peaks at L33
key_evidence: N29:4973 (0.85 proj) — T-specific neuron also voting for Y and N
N31:3485 (0.95 proj) — strongest T writer in decision phase
F33:9048 (attn, 82.9 proj) — final-layer T prediction channel

candidates.narrative: Proline remains negligible (<3%) through L29, then surges dramatically in L32-33 via late MLP activation, reaching 24% final probability. This late emergence suggests proline-specific prediction neurons firing in response to the turn context assembled earlier. The surge is too late and too weak to challenge threonine's established lead, but represents a genuine alternative interpretation of the beta-turn structural requirement. Key support comes from very late MLP neurons that recognize turn-compatible residues.
key_evidence: Rises from 0.7% (L29) to 23.6% (L33) in final layers
L32-33 MLP activity drives the surge (no specific high-projection P neurons visible in top writers)

candidates.narrative: Serine leads the logit lens at L0 (22.6%) and remains prominent through L14 (15%), reflecting the representation's initial polar character. This early prominence is NOT a prediction — it indicates the embedding and early layers encode polar, hydroxyl-bearing chemistry consistent with the local sequence context. S fades as more specific turn-context features accumulate (drops to 5% by L23), then resurges briefly in L31 (peaks at 31.4%) before T's final dominance. The L31 peak reflects S-specific prediction channels activating but losing to stronger T evidence.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L0-1, fades L8-23, brief resurgence L31
key_evidence: 22.6% at L0 — embedding encodes polar hydroxyl character
Peaks at 31.4% L31 before final T surge
N12:1284 (0.18 proj to T) votes even more strongly for S (0.34 proj)

candidates.narrative: Alanine peaks at 20% in L12-13 during the perception phase, reflecting a hydrophobic-leaning representation character as the model integrates structural contacts. This is not a prediction but rather indicates the accumulated features at L12 correlate with small hydrophobic residues. The representation character shifts away from hydrophobicity as turn-specific features emerge in L14-23, and A drops to 3.5% by L23. A brief resurgence to 20% at L31 suggests late hydrophobic prediction channels activating, but these are overwhelmed by polar evidence.
key_evidence: 20% at L12 — representation has hydrophobic character mid-perception
N13:2008 (0.22 proj to T) votes more strongly for A (0.33 proj) and L (0.27 proj)
Drops to 5.9% final as polar evidence dominates

candidates.narrative: Valine briefly dominates the logit lens at L17-26, peaking at 41.5% at L26 before T overtakes it. This reflects the representation's compatibility with hydrophobic beta-strand residues during the late perception phase. V's prominence is driven by structural context features that recognize buried, hydrophobic positions. However, as AA-specific prediction channels activate in L26-32, T's polar hydroxyl group proves more compatible with the turn requirement, and V drops to near-zero by L33.
key_evidence: 41.5% at L26 — strongest logit-lens signal before decision phase
Drops precipitously L26-33 as T-specific neurons activate
Represents hydrophobic strand interpretation of context

turning_points.description: The representation character shifts rapidly through hydrophobic and charged phases as early attention heads read local sequence without clear structural focus. L8 head 6 writes +4.1 toward the answer without attending to structural contacts, suggesting abstract sequence pattern recognition. The logit lens shows 6 lead changes in this range (L→K→L→S→A→R) as different chemical features accumulate. This volatility reflects the model assembling multiple competing interpretations of the local context before turn-specific features stabilize the representation.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. L23 shows T at 27.5% with general polar representation. L24-25 activate the first AA-specific prediction channels: L25 MLP contributes +4.7 net T projection with explicit T-voting neurons (N25:816, N25:2435). L26 delivers +6.7 logit velocity (MLP-driven) with N26:2159 projecting 0.73 toward T. This is when the model commits: the representation shifts from 'polar turn position' to 'specifically threonine,' and T takes the logit-lens lead from V.

The decisive push occurs in these layers through sustained MLP neuron activation. L29-31 show the strongest T-writing neurons in the entire network: N29:4973 (0.85 proj), N30:1323 (0.69 proj), N31:3485 (0.95 proj). T rises from 38% to 46% across this range. L32 shows a dramatic proline surge (+11.1 MLP delta) as late turn-recognition neurons activate, but this is insufficient to overcome T's established lead. L32 attention head 16 erases -4.5 from T by attending to structural contacts, but MLP support maintains T's dominance.

deep_dives.caption: Watch the transition from context to prediction. L24 shows mixed MLP activity (net -2.1 proj). L25 activates first T-specific neurons: N25:816 (0.68 proj), N25:2435 (0.51 proj), contributing +4.7 net. L26 delivers the commitment: N26:2159 (0.73 proj) and +2.6 net MLP push. This is where AA-specific prediction channels first dominate.

deep_dives.caption: The strongest T-writing neurons in the network fire here. N29:4973 (0.85 proj), N30:1323 (0.69 proj), N31:3485 (0.95 proj) cast explicit T votes. L29-31 contribute +18.8 cumulative net MLP projection. Compare top_writers to see how these neurons vote for T specifically versus other polar residues.

deep_dives.caption: L32 MLP contributes +11.1 toward T but also activates proline-specific channels, causing P to surge from 0.7% to 23.6%. Examine which neurons vote for P and why this late turn-recognition signal emerges. Note that T-writing neurons (N32:4002, N32:662, N32:1469) still dominate with 0.78-0.79 projections.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features L30-33
deep_dives.caption: L30-33 features encode the final T prediction. F30:9045 (57.6 proj attn) and F33:9048 (82.9 proj attn) are high-confidence T-specific channels. F33:4166 (78.4 proj) and F33:6423 (76.2 proj) provide additional T support. These features represent the model's final committed prediction state.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts threonine by assembling a polar beta-turn context through L1-23, then activating T-specific prediction channels in L26-32. The decisive evidence comes from sustained MLP neuron support (N29:4973, N30:1323, N31:3485 projecting 0.69-0.95) that recognizes threonine's hydroxyl group as optimal for the turn position. The volatile early logit lens (10 lead changes L1-17) reflects the model exploring multiple chemical interpretations before turn-context features stabilize the representation. Proline's late surge (24% final) represents a genuine alternative turn-compatible solution, but T's earlier commitment and stronger cumulative evidence (48% vs 24%) secure the correct prediction.
